environmental policy which is dominated by industrialized states? This book extends the debate both within and across disciplines, engaging philosophers, geographers, political scientists, economists, sociologists, and environmental activists from four continents. The essays address the role of science in global change and argue that western science does not provide morally disinterested solutions to environmental problems. They discuss the role of state and substate actors in the international politics of the environment, and then use accounts of actual negotiations to argue for the centrality of social justice in reaching desirable and equitable agreements. They conclude that a framework for social justice under conditions of global environmental change must include community values and provide for participatory structures to arbitrate among competing interests.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aConservation of natural resources. 0aEnvironmental policyxEconomic aspects. 0aSocial justice. 4aEnvironmental History. 4aPhilosophy. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aCamilleri, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonner, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHampson, Fen Osler, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHampson, Fen Osler, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJasanoff, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, David B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKothari, Smitu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKymlicka, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaberge, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.